g. He later claimed that he \"didn't think the gun would fire\". A 17-year-old male student in the classroom was wounded after he was shot in the ankle. Bouche then entered the classroom of one of his former teachers, and surrendered peacefully to the responding SRO. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ocala.com/news/20190420/one-year-after-shooting-at-ocalas-forest-high-school|title=One year after the shooting at Ocala\u2019s Forest High School |date=April 20, 2019 |work=OcalaStarBanner}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{Dts|April 27, 2018}}\n|[[Shaanxi]], China\n| Zhao, 28\n| 9 dead\n| 10 injured\n| Nine students were stabbed to death and 10 injured in a knife attack outside a school in northern China. The man who carried out the attack was reportedly a former student, taking revenge for having been bullied at the school. The dead were seven girls and two boys aged 12 to 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-43921567|title=China stabbings: Nine students killed in Shaanxi |date=April 28, 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n|-\n|May 25, 2018\n|[[Palmdale, California]], US\n| -\n| -\n|1 injured\n|A 14 year old male opened fire with a rifle at roughly 7:00&nbsp;a.m. at [[Highland High School (Palmdale, California)|Highland High School]] campus and then walked into a bathroom, The shots wounded one former schoolmate, a male who was shot in his arm. The suspect shot 10 rounds. He then dumped the gun in a field before he was taken into custody in a nearby shopping center.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2018/05/11/deputies-respond-to-report-of-man-with-a-gun-at-palmdales-highland-high-school//|title= Student shot at Highland High School in Palmdale, former schoolmate in custody |last=|first=|date=2018-05-18|work=CBS Interactive Inc.|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|May 18, 2018\n|[[Santa Fe, Texas]], US\n|Dimitrios Pagourtzis, 17\n|10 dead\n|14 injured\n|[[Santa Fe High School shooting]]. A student armed with a shotgun and a .38 revolver smuggled under his coat opened fire on [[Santa Fe High School (Texas)|Santa Fe High School]] campus, killing 10 people and wounding 13 more, as well as injuring himself.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/18/us/school-shooting-santa-fe-texas.html|title=Texas School Shooting: 10 Dead, 10 Hurt, and Many Not Surprised It Happened|last=Fernandez|first=Manny|date=2018-05-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-05-19|last2=Fausset|first2=Richard|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Bidgood|first3=Jess}}</ref>\n|-\n|May 25, 2018\n|[[Noblesville, Indiana]], US\n| Student, 13\n| -\n|2 injured\n|[[Noblesville West Middle School shooting]]. A student opened fire at 9:06.<ref name=\"f59-what-we-know\">{{cite news|title=Here\u2019s what we know about the Noblesville West Middle School shooting that injured student, teacher|url=http://fox59.com/2018/05/25/heres-what-we-know-about-the-noblesville-west-middle-school-shooting/|accessdate=25 May 2018|agency=FOX59}}</ref> a.m. on [[Noblesville West Middle School]] campus, injuring two; an adult and a teenager. After the incident, the suspect came into custody.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/indiana-school-shooting-report-of-shots-fired-at-noblesville-west-middle-school/|title=Police: 2 injured in shooting at Noblesville West Middle School in Indiana|last=|first=|date=2018-05-18|work=CBS Interactive Inc.|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|October 17, 2018\n|[[Kerch]]\n| Vladislav Roslyakov, 18\n|21 dead\n|70 injured\n|The [[Kerch Polytechnic College massacre]]. An 18-year-old student at the [[Kerch Polytechnic College]] set off explosives in the school and began shooting, killing 20. The shooter was highly inspired by the [[Columbine High School Massacre]], even going as far as wearing the same clothes as one of the two shooters involved in that attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45891201|title=Gun attack at Crimea college kills 19|date=October 17, 2018|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|December 17, 2018\n|[[Haridwar, Uttarakhand]], India\n| Student, 13\n| -\n|1 injured\n| DAV Public School shooting in Haridwar\n|-\n|February 11, 2019\n|[[Stowbtsy]], Belarus\n| Student, 15\n| 2 dead\n| 2 injured\n| A 15-year-old student stabbed a 50-year-old history teacher in the neck, who then died on the spot. He also stabbed two students, who tried to defend the teacher, injuring both of them. The assailant then left the class and entered a nearby classroom, where he stabbed a 17-year-old student, who also died on the spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/belarusian-teen-suspected-of-stabbing-teacher-classmate-to-death/29763228.html|title=Belarusian Teen Suspected Of Stabbing Teacher, Classmate To Death |date=February 11, 2019 |work=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 26, 2019\n|[[Toronto]], Ontario\n| Unknown\n| \n| 2 injured\n| A fight between two students ended off with a double stabbing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/02/26/stabbing-york-memorial-collegiate/|title=2 students stabbed outside York Memorial Collegiate Institute |date=February 26, 2019 |work=CityNews}}</ref>\n|-\n|March 13, 2019\n|[[Suzano]], Brazil\n| Guilherme Taucci Monteiro, 17; Luiz Henrique de Castro, 25\n| 10 dead\n| 11 injured\n| [[Suzano massacre|Two masked]] men shot and killed 6 students and 2 staff members at a public secondary school in Suzano, Brazil. Eleven additional victims were wounded. The suspects committed suicide inside the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/13/americas/brazil-school-shooting/index.html/|title=At least 8 people were killed in a school shooting in Brazil |date=March 13, 2019 |work=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 7, 2019\n| Colorado, United States\n| Devon Erickson, 18; Maya Elizabeth, 16\n| 1 dead\n| 8 injured\n| At the [[STEM School Highlands Ranch]] two suspects, who were students at the school, injured eight students and killed one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/08/us/denver-stem-shooting-heroes-run-hide-fight/index.html|title=Again in the age of 'run, hide, fight,' student heroes thwart a school shooter|first=Eliott C.|last= McLaughlin|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/08/us/kendrick-castillo-denver-stem-shooting/index.html|title=This student died trying to stop the Colorado school shooter|author1=Nicole Chavez |author2=Scott McLean|website=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 28, 2019\n| Volsk, Saratov Region, Russia\n| Daniil Pulkin\n| \n| 1 injured\n| In the afternoon of May 28, the teenager came to school with a bag containing an axe and molotov cocktails inside. First, Pulkin attempted to burn the office of his former form mistress. After that, he hit a 6th grader girl in the head with an axe.\n|-\n| August 8, 2019\n| Montgomery, Alabama\n| Isaiah Johnson, 38\n| 0\n| 0\n| 38-year old Isaiah Johnson dropped his son off at Blount Elementary School, and then got into an argument with another father over a traffic dispute. He then discharged a firearm into the other father's vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvtm13.com/article/2-arrested-after-road-rage-shooting-at-alabama-elementary-school/28647302|title=Back-to-school traffic leads to argument, shooting outside Alabama elementary school|first=The Associated|last=Press|date=August 8, 2019|website=WVTM}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apr.org/post/mental-evaluation-sought-school-traffic-shooting-suspect|title=Mental evaluation sought for school traffic shooting suspect|first=Associated|last=Press|website=www.apr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/crime/2019/08/26/isaiah-johnson-charged-escape-after-blount-elementary-shooting/2121409001/|title=Father charged in Blount Elementary shooting re-arrested after escaping treatment facility|first=Melissa|last=Brown|website=The Montgomery Advertiser}}</ref>\n|-\n| August 30, 2019\n| Mobile, Alabama\n| Deangelo Dejuan Parnell, 17\n| 0\n| 10 injured\n| Parnell shot 9 people during a confrontation at a stadium where a high school football game was being played. A tenth person suffered a stroke.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/31/us/mobile-alabama-football-shooting.html|title=At Least 10 Shot at Alabama High School Football Game, Police Say|first=Derrick Bryson|last=Taylor|date=August 31, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 1, 2019\n| [[Kuopio]], Finland\n| Joel Marin, 25\n| 1 dead\n| 10 injured\n| [[Kuopio school stabbing]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019 \n| Santa Clarita, California\n| Nathaniel Berhow, 16\n| 3 dead\n| 3 injured \n| [[Saugus High School shooting]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019\n| [[Blagoveshchensk]], Russia\n| Daniil Zasorin, 19\n| 3 dead\n| 2 injured\n| After being told to leave the classroom twice, Zasorin returned with a pump-action shotgun and opened fire in the room, shooting victims at their desks. He committed suicide after being wounded in exchange of gunfire with police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-college-shooting-daniil-zasorin-attack-death-toll-latest-today-a9202526.html|title=Gunman opens fire in deadly Russian college attack after posting bizarre message online|date=14 November 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[School bullying]]\n*[[School shooting]]\n*[[List of school-related attacks]]\n*[[List of school shootings in the United States]]\n*[[List of attacks related to primary schools]]\n*[[List of attacks related to post-secondary schools]]\n*[[List of rampage killers: School massacres]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n<ref name=note_a>Including death or injury of attacker(s), when applicable.</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181140/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence00-01.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2000\u20132001], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181216/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence02-03.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2002\u20132003], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181239/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence04-05.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2004\u20132005], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181347/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence06-07.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2006\u20132007], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181441/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence07-08.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2007\u20132008], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181632/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence08-09.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2008\u20132009], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181945/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence09-10.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2009\u20132010], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:School-Related Attacks}}\n[[Category:Attacks on schools|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of schools|*]]\n[[Category:Crime-related lists]]\n[[Category:Secondary education-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of school-related attacks|secondary]]\n", "name_user": "BorderRegions", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2010s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_attacks_related_to_secondary_schools"}
{"title_page": "Mamta Sagar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian writer}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{MOS|date=April 2017}}\n{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2018}}\n{{overly detailed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Underlinked|date=August 2019}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Mamta Sagar\n| image         = File:MamtabyChukki.jpg\n| nationality   = Indian\n| occupation    = Writer, translater\n| years_active  = 1992-present\n}}\n\n'''Mamta Sagar''' is a poet, writer, academic, translator and an activist writing in [[Kannada]] language.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Subramaniam |first1=Arundhathi |title=Mamta Sagar (poet) - India |url=https://www.poetryinternational.org/pi/poet/13507/Mamta-Sagar/en/tile |website=Poetry International Archives |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Her writings focus on identity politics, feminism, issues around linguistic and cultural diversities. She is a professor of Academic and Creative Writing at Srishti Institute of Art, Design and Technology.<ref>{{cite web |title=Teaching Faculty |url=http://www.srishti.ac.in/people/faculty |website=Srishti Institute of Art, Design and Technology |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education and Career==\n\nSagar has a PhD in Comparative Literature from [[University of Hyderabad|Hyderabad Central University]]. Mamta has worked with Hyderabad Central University and [[Bangalore University]] where she has taught Comparative Literature, Translation Studies, Kannada Literature, Feminism, Postcolonial and Cultural Studies. Her doctoral work is in Comparative Literature from University of Hyderabad and the thesis is titled as \u201c''Gender, Patriarchy and Resistance: Contemporary Women\u2019s Poetry in Kannada and Hindi (1980\u20132000)''\u201d. She has a specialization in Comparative Literature, Gender Studies, Kannada Literature and Cultural Discourse. Sagar received the Charles Wallace India Trust fellowship in 2015.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Notes\n|-\n| ''Kaada Navilina Hejje'' (Footprints of The Wild Peacock) || 1992 ||poetry collection\n|-\n|''Chukki Chukki Chandakki''|| 1993 || a play for children, directed by Iqbal Ahmed in Bangalore\n|- \n| ''Nadiya Neerina Teva'' (Dampness of the River) || 1999 ||poetry collection\n|-\n| ''Hiige Haaleya Maile Haadu'' (Like this the song) || 2007 || poetry collection\n|-\n| ''Growing Up As A Woman Writer'' || 2007 ||\n|- \n|''MahiLa Vishaya'' || 2007 || collection of essays in Kannada and English on gender, language, literature, and culture\n|-\n| ''Illi Salluva Maatu'' || 2010 || collection of column writings published by Chaitrapallavi Prakashana, 2010\n|-\n| ''Hide & Seek''|| 2014|| a collection of selected poems in English with the source text in Kannada\n|-\n| ''kShaNabindu'' || 2018|| poetry collection; in collaboration with Vasu Dixit & Bindumalini\n|-\n| ''Interversions'' || - || a compilation of collaborative poetry activities\n|}\n[[File:KShaNabindu.jpg|alt=KShaNabindu|thumb|(from right) Mamta Sagar, Vasu Dixit, and Bindumalini at a poetry event {{when|date=April 2020}}{{where|date=April 2020}} |left]]\n\n\n===Notable translation work===\n\n* ''Preetiya Nalavattu NiyamagaLu'' (2017), a translation of Elif Shafak's novel into Kannada\n* ''870'' (2011) by Emily Dickinson into Kannada\n* ''Seemantha'' (2003), a Kannada short story by Nagaveni into English\n* ''The Swing of Desire'', translation of the Kannada play 'Mayye Bhaara Manave Bhaara', included in the anthology, \"Staging Resistance: Plays by Women in Translation\", edited and introduced by Tutun Mukherjee. Oxford University Press, New Delhi. 2004.\n* ''Beyond Barriers: Slovenian-Kannada Literature Interactions'', a trilingual compilation of poems and short stories (2011)\n* Poems by Tirumalamba, the first woman poet among the early modern Kannada, into English\n* Poems by Slovenian poets Brane Mozetic and Veronika Dintinjana and Slovenian Short story writers Andrej Blatnik and Suzana Tratnik into Kannada for the book, 'Slovenian-Kannada Literature Interactions' edited by her for Centre for Slovenian Literature, Ljubljana, Slovenia 2011.\n* Translated many passages into Kannada for Tim Supples's production of Shakespeare's play 'A ''Midsummer Nights Dream', 2008.''\n* Co-translated the Kannada play \u201c''MAHA CHAITRA''\u201d into Malayalam with Dr Chitra Panikkar, Published in 'Kerala Kavitha 2000' edited by Dr. K. Ayyappa Panikkar, January 2000, Calicut.\n\n==Other notable work==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\nSagar has translated poetry, prose, and critical writings into Kannada and English, and has collaborated with the translation activity in many Indian and foreign languages. Her poems have been translated into many Indian languages including English apart from Spanish, French, Vietnamese, Galician, Maltese, Japanese, Chinese, Slovenian, Serbian, Russian, Cebuano. Her poems have been subscribed for textbooks from Jain University, Bangalore and University of Kerala. Some of her poems are composed with music by known musicians Vasu Dixit,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Deepika |first1=K. C. |title=Introducing Kannada classics in rock form |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/introducing-kannada-classics-in-rock-form/article17413506.ece |website=The Hindu |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Bindumalini and Sunitha Ananthaswamy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Song - Slaughter |url=https://avadhimag.com/?p=148999 |website=I - Awadhi |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\u00a0\n\nSagar produced ''INTERVERSIONS 1,2,&3'', three poetry films based on her own poetry collection of the same name, with Srishti Films as part of the Wales-India collaborative projects (2018). She has also written and produced ''FOR GAURI'', a video presentation of her poem written for [[Gauri Lankesh]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aji |first1=Sowmya |title=Poetry flowed like blood and tears at a rally in Bengaluru this week to protest the murder of Gauri Lankesh|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/poetry-flowed-like-blood-and-tears-at-a-rally-in-bengaluru-this-week-to-protest-the-murder-of-gauri-lankesh/articleshow/60715375.cms |website=Economic Times |publisher=India Times |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSagar has toured with Mark Gwynne Jones in India and UK on 'Melding Voices', the UK Arts Council Funded projects. She was interviewed and included in the documentary, 'Cultures of Resistance' directed by Iara Lee. Her poetry and interviews were showcased in 'Los ''Chicos de Ma\u00f1ana''' a documentary directed by Javier Monero for Flying cat Productions, Spain. A collection of her poems have been published in Spanish in ''Caratula'' (Edici\u00f3n No. 35, Abril \u2013 Mayo 2010. Director: Sergio Ram\u00edrez. Editor: Francisco Ruiz Udiel, Nicaragua). ''Como esto en la pagina la cancion'' is another collection of her poems in Spanish translated by Nicol\u00e1s Suesc\u00fan and Nelson Roque Vald\u00e9s (2008). \n\nSagar has curated many international and national poetry and theatre events in Hyderabad and Bangalore including 'Kaavya Sanje', a multilingual community poetry event at the Bangalore Literature Festival, and is actively involved with international poetry translation projects. She conducted a poetry workshop in Durban, South Africa in 2005.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\n* 2012 - AUROPOLIS Poet in Residence\n* 2019 - Sanchi Honnamma Kaavya Prashasti\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://archive.is/20130418134022/http://www.uni-aas.si/2010/05/17-literarno-glasbeni-festival-ziva-knjizevnost Ljubljana Poetry Festival, Slovenia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120426071959/http://www.ccp.si/english/izpis.php?id=873 International Poetry Translation Workshop, Dane, Sezana, Slovenia]\n*[https://archive.is/20130221102654/http://www.caratula.net/archivo/N35-0410/poesia-sagar.php GRANADA POETRY FESTIVAL 2010, NICARAGUA]\n*[http://tongocthach.vn/index.php?loading=6&sid=032afd896fe76&title=index&setallid=010000110111000111001100111&group_id=23&new_id=894&cap=T%E1%BA%A1p%20v%C4%83n%20%28Miscellanea%29 Literature Festival, Hanoi-Ha long bay, Vietnam 2010]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120525050127/http://www.festivaldepoesiademedellin.org/pub.php/en/Revista/ultimas_ediciones/81_82/sagar.html International Poetry Festival of Medellin,Colombia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190307173945/http://www.cca.ukzn.ac.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=281:mamta-sagar-india&catid=31:participant-bios&Itemid=1 Poetry Africa 2005]\n*[http://www.womenswriting.com/writerdetails.asp?writerid=24 Seemantha, Translated By Mamta G Sagar]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110715101325/http://www.poemsabout.com/poet/mamta-g-sagar/ Best Poems from Mamta G. Sagar]\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2007/03/10/stories/2007031019650200.htm MahiLa Vishaya Book launch in Hyderabad]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sagar, Mamta}}\n[[Category:Indian women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kannada poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian women poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women translators]]\n[[Category:Dramatists and playwrights from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Poets from Karnataka]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian writer}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{MOS|date=April 2017}}\n{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2018}}\n{{overly detailed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Underlinked|date=August 2019}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Mamta Sagar\n| image         = File:MamtabyChukki.jpg\n| nationality   = Indian\n| occupation    = Writer, translater\n| years_active  = 1992-present\n}}\n\n'''Mamta Sagar''' is a poet, writer, academic, translator and an activist writing in [[Kannada]] language.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Subramaniam |first1=Arundhathi |title=Mamta Sagar (poet) - India |url=https://www.poetryinternational.org/pi/poet/13507/Mamta-Sagar/en/tile |website=Poetry International Archives |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Her writings focus on identity politics, feminism, issues around linguistic and cultural diversities. She is a professor of Academic and Creative Writing at Srishti Institute of Art, Design and Technology.<ref>{{cite web |title=Teaching Faculty |url=http://www.srishti.ac.in/people/faculty |website=Srishti Institute of Art, Design and Technology |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education and Career==\n\nSagar has a PhD in Comparative Literature from [[University of Hyderabad|Hyderabad Central University]]. Mamta has worked with Hyderabad Central University and [[Bangalore University]] where she has taught Comparative Literature, Translation Studies, Kannada Literature, Feminism, Postcolonial and Cultural Studies. Her doctoral work is in Comparative Literature from University of Hyderabad and the thesis is titled as \u201c''Gender, Patriarchy and Resistance: Contemporary Women\u2019s Poetry in Kannada and Hindi (1980\u20132000)''\u201d. She has a specialization in Comparative Literature, Gender Studies, Kannada Literature and Cultural Discourse. Sagar recieved the Charles Wallace India Trust fellowship in 2015.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Notes\n|-\n| ''Kaada Navilina Hejje'' (Footprints of The Wild Peacock) || 1992 ||poetry collection\n|-\n|''Chukki Chukki Chandakki''|| 1993 || a play for children, directed by Iqbal Ahmed in Bangalore\n|- \n| ''Nadiya Neerina Teva'' (Dampness of the River) || 1999 ||poetry collection\n|-\n| ''Hiige Haaleya Maile Haadu'' (Like this the song) || 2007 || poetry collection\n|-\n| ''Growing Up As A Woman Writer'' || 2007 ||\n|- \n|''MahiLa Vishaya'' || 2007 || collection of essays in Kannada and English on gender, language, literature, and culture\n|-\n| ''Illi Salluva Maatu'' || 2010 || collection of column writings published by Chaitrapallavi Prakashana, 2010\n|-\n| ''Hide & Seek''|| 2014|| a collection of selected poems in English with the source text in Kannada\n|-\n| ''kShaNabindu'' || 2018|| poetry collection; in collaboration with Vasu Dixit & Bindumalini\n|-\n| ''Interversions'' || - || a compilation of collaborative poetry activities\n|}\n[[File:KShaNabindu.jpg|alt=KShaNabindu|thumb|(from right) Mamta Sagar, Vasu Dixit, and Bindumalini at a poetry event {{when|date=April 2020}}{{where|date=April 2020}} |left]]\n\n\n===Notable translation work===\n\n* ''Preetiya Nalavattu NiyamagaLu'' (2017), a translation of Elif Shafak's novel into Kannada\n* ''870'' (2011) by Emily Dickinson into Kannada\n* ''Seemantha'' (2003), a Kannada short story by Nagaveni into English\n* ''The Swing of Desire'', translation of the Kannada play 'Mayye Bhaara Manave Bhaara', included in the anthology, \"Staging Resistance: Plays by Women in Translation\", edited and introduced by Tutun Mukherjee. Oxford University Press, New Delhi. 2004.\n* ''Beyond Barriers: Slovenian-Kannada Literature Interactions'', a trilingual compilation of poems and short stories (2011)\n* Poems by Tirumalamba, the first woman poet among the early modern Kannada, into English\n* Poems by Slovenian poets Brane Mozetic and Veronika Dintinjana and Slovenian Short story writers Andrej Blatnik and Suzana Tratnik into Kannada for the book, 'Slovenian-Kannada Literature Interactions' edited by her for Centre for Slovenian Literature, Ljubljana, Slovenia 2011.\n* Translated many passages into Kannada for Tim Supples's production of Shakespeare's play 'A ''Midsummer Nights Dream', 2008.''\n* Co-translated the Kannada play \u201c''MAHA CHAITRA''\u201d into Malayalam with Dr Chitra Panikkar, Published in 'Kerala Kavitha 2000' edited by Dr. K. Ayyappa Panikkar, January 2000, Calicut.\n\n==Other notable work==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\nSagar has translated poetry, prose, and critical writings into Kannada and English, and has collaborated with the translation activity in many Indian and foreign languages. Her poems have been translated into many Indian languages including English apart from Spanish, French, Vietnamese, Galician, Maltese, Japanese, Chinese, Slovenian, Serbian, Russian, Cebuano. Her poems have been subscribed for textbooks from Jain University, Bangalore and University of Kerala. Some of her poems are composed with music by known musicians Vasu Dixit,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Deepika |first1=K. C. |title=Introducing Kannada classics in rock form |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/introducing-kannada-classics-in-rock-form/article17413506.ece |website=The Hindu |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Bindumalini and Sunitha Ananthaswamy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Song - Slaughter |url=https://avadhimag.com/?p=148999 |website=I - Awadhi |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\u00a0\n\nSagar produced ''INTERVERSIONS 1,2,&3'', three poetry films based on her own poetry collection of the same name, with Srishti Films as part of the Wales-India collaborative projects (2018). She has also written and produced ''FOR GAURI'', a video presentation of her poem written for [[Gauri Lankesh]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aji |first1=Sowmya |title=Poetry flowed like blood and tears at a rally in Bengaluru this week to protest the murder of Gauri Lankesh|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/poetry-flowed-like-blood-and-tears-at-a-rally-in-bengaluru-this-week-to-protest-the-murder-of-gauri-lankesh/articleshow/60715375.cms |website=Economic Times |publisher=India Times |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSagar has toured with Mark Gwynne Jones in India and UK on 'Melding Voices', the UK Arts Council Funded projects. She was interviewed and included in the documentary, 'Cultures of Resistance' directed by Iara Lee. Her poetry and interviews were showcased in 'Los ''Chicos de Ma\u00f1ana''' a documentary directed by Javier Monero for Flying cat Productions, Spain. A collection of her poems have been published in Spanish in ''Caratula'' (Edici\u00f3n No. 35, Abril \u2013 Mayo 2010. Director: Sergio Ram\u00edrez. Editor: Francisco Ruiz Udiel, Nicaragua). ''Como esto en la pagina la cancion'' is another collection of her poems in Spanish translated by Nicol\u00e1s Suesc\u00fan and Nelson Roque Vald\u00e9s (2008). \n\nSagar has curated many international and national poetry and theatre events in Hyderabad and Bangalore including 'Kaavya Sanje', a multilingual community poetry event at the Bangalore Literature Festival, and is actively involved with international poetry translation projects. She conducted a poetry workshop in Durban, South Africa in 2005.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\n* 2012 - AUROPOLIS Poet in Residence\n* 2019 - Sanchi Honnamma Kaavya Prashasti\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://archive.is/20130418134022/http://www.uni-aas.si/2010/05/17-literarno-glasbeni-festival-ziva-knjizevnost Ljubljana Poetry Festival, Slovenia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120426071959/http://www.ccp.si/english/izpis.php?id=873 International Poetry Translation Workshop, Dane, Sezana, Slovenia]\n*[https://archive.is/20130221102654/http://www.caratula.net/archivo/N35-0410/poesia-sagar.php GRANADA POETRY FESTIVAL 2010, NICARAGUA]\n*[http://tongocthach.vn/index.php?loading=6&sid=032afd896fe76&title=index&setallid=010000110111000111001100111&group_id=23&new_id=894&cap=T%E1%BA%A1p%20v%C4%83n%20%28Miscellanea%29 Literature Festival, Hanoi-Ha long bay, Vietnam 2010]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120525050127/http://www.festivaldepoesiademedellin.org/pub.php/en/Revista/ultimas_ediciones/81_82/sagar.html International Poetry Festival of Medellin,Colombia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190307173945/http://www.cca.ukzn.ac.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=281:mamta-sagar-india&catid=31:participant-bios&Itemid=1 Poetry Africa 2005]\n*[http://www.womenswriting.com/writerdetails.asp?writerid=24 Seemantha, Translated By Mamta G Sagar]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110715101325/http://www.poemsabout.com/poet/mamta-g-sagar/ Best Poems from Mamta G. Sagar]\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2007/03/10/stories/2007031019650200.htm MahiLa Vishaya Book launch in Hyderabad]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sagar, Mamta}}\n[[Category:Indian women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kannada poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian women poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women translators]]\n[[Category:Dramatists and playwrights from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Poets from Karnataka]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mamta_Sagar"}
{"title_page": "Tornadoes of 2020", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 - ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]]\n|max_date      = March 3\n|max_location2  = [[Jayess, Mississippi]]\n|max_date2      = April 12\n|max_location3  = [[Bassfield, Mississippi]]\n|max_date3      = April 12\n|tornadoes_usa = 370\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion total economic losses\n|total_fatalities_world = 66\n|total_fatalities_usa = 66\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 456 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 370 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 66 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 370\n|FU = 7\n|F0 = 114\n|F1 = 179\n|F2 = 53\n|F3 = 14\n|F4 = 3\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 87 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 - 02/06/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, heavy rainfall resulted in widespread flooding also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 77 were confirmed. Although March was slightly below average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF4 damage in a residential area near Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2-3, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 14 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nOn March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event - Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> With severe storms continuing into the early morning hours of March 19, two EF2 tornadoes caused considerable damage to trees, vehicles, farming equipment, and outbuildings near [[Trent, Texas]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce another EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars at a correctional facility northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]. Near [[Sweetwater, Texas|Sweetwater]], an EF2 tornado damaged or destroyed several wind turbines.<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/> Later that day, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms, along with parts of the [[Ohio Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]] before moving through the southeastern part of town, causing significant damage to homes, a school, outbuildings, and trees.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes also touched down in Arkansas, one of which tracked between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], inflicting considerable damage to some homes. Further north, two EF1 tornadoes caused damage in [[Sunfield, Illinois|Sunfield]] and [[Dahlgren, Illinois]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another injury occurred in Arkansas. A total of 21 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nOn March 28, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of Illinois, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. An enhanced risk of severe weather was in place \nacross parts of Iowa, Missouri, Indiana, and Arkansas as well. Only weak tornadoes touched down in the moderate risk area, though a few strong tornadoes occurred elsewhere. A large EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage to homes, businesses, and a shopping mall. Vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the local airport sustained severe damage as well. A train was also derailed, and 22 injuries occurred in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC - 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]]. This included an EF1 tornado caused moderate damage to apartment buildings and trees in [[Oelwein, Iowa]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nA low-end EF2 tornado moved through the southern fringes of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying numerous outbuildings and a barn, and damaging dozens of homes and trees.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 struck the town of [[Newburgh, Indiana]], where five homes sustained partial to total roof removal, and one home had a few upper floor exterior walls ripped off. Numerous other homes in town sustained less severe damage, and two people were injured in Newburgh.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 20 tornadoes.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, producing several tornadoes across parts of the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nA high-end EF2 tornado caused significant damage just south of [[Eufaula, Alabama]], where multiple homes in a subdivision had their roofs torn off. A few of these homes sustained partial exterior wall loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Multiple other weak tornadoes were confirmed in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> A landspout tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT at the north edge of [[Richland, Washington]], causing no damage. A total of 15 tornadoes are confirmed.<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 164 tornadoes confirmed in the United States in April.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA few weak tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8, causing tree and structure damage. Later on the night of April 8, a large EF2 cone tornado touched down near [[Weiner, Arkansas]], completely destroying a mobile home. The tornado then struck [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one frail home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged or destroyed in residential areas of town.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Extensive tree damage occurred and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> Numerous tornadoes, all of which weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio that night as well. One EF1 tornado caused considerable damage to a brick building in downtown [[Mooresville, Indiana]]. Another EF1 tornado damaged two mobile homes, a garage, and trees near [[Wilkesville, Ohio]] on April 9 before the outbreak came to an end. Numerous reports of damaging straight line winds were also received throughout the event. A total of 31 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 29|F1 = 68|F2 = 21|F3 = 12|F4 = 2|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\nFrom the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major tornado outbreak unfolded across the [[Southeastern United States]], with more than 100 tornadoes touching down in 24 hours over two days. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 131 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Maryland. This event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city limits causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce three intense long-tracked tornadoes, including two rated EF4, that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center - PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. At 6:55 a.m. EDT, an embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another tornado emergency as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Nine EF3 tornadoes occurred on day two of the outbreak, including seven in [[South Carolina]] that resulted in a combined eight deaths, most notably the 3/4-mile wide EF3 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina|Hampton County]] that took the lives of five people near the towns of [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and Nixville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nWith 32 confirmed fatalities, it was the deadliest outbreak since the [[Tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 - ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]]\n|max_date      = March 3\n|max_location2  = [[Jayess, Mississippi]]\n|max_date2      = April 12\n|max_location3  = [[Bassfield, Mississippi]]\n|max_date3      = April 12\n|tornadoes_usa = 370\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion total economic losses\n|total_fatalities_world = 66\n|total_fatalities_usa = 66\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 456 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 370 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 66 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 370\n|FU = 7\n|F0 = 114\n|F1 = 179\n|F2 = 53\n|F3 = 14\n|F4 = 3\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 87 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 - 02/06/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, heavy rainfall resulted in widespread flooding also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 77 were confirmed. Although March was slightly below average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF4 damage in a residential area near Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2-3, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 14 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nOn March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event - Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> With severe storms continuing into the early morning hours of March 19, two EF2 tornadoes caused considerable damage to trees, vehicles, farming equipment, and outbuildings near [[Trent, Texas]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce another EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars at a correctional facility northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]. Near [[Sweetwater, Texas|Sweetwater]], an EF2 tornado damaged or destroyed several wind turbines.<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/> Later that day, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms, along with parts of the [[Ohio Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]] before moving through the southeastern part of town, causing significant damage to homes, a school, outbuildings, and trees.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes also touched down in Arkansas, one of which tracked between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], inflicting considerable damage to some homes. Further north, two EF1 tornadoes caused damage in [[Sunfield, Illinois|Sunfield]] and [[Dahlgren, Illinois]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another injury occurred in Arkansas. A total of 21 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nOn March 28, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of Illinois, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. An enhanced risk of severe weather was in place \nacross parts of Iowa, Missouri, Indiana, and Arkansas as well. Only weak tornadoes touched down in the moderate risk area, though a few strong tornadoes occurred elsewhere. A large EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage to homes, businesses, and a shopping mall. Vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the local airport sustained severe damage as well. A train was also derailed, and 22 injuries occurred in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC - 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]]. This included an EF1 tornado caused moderate damage to apartment buildings and trees in [[Oelwein, Iowa]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nA low-end EF2 tornado moved through the southern fringes of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying numerous outbuildings and a barn, and damaging dozens of homes and trees.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 struck the town of [[Newburgh, Indiana]], where five homes sustained partial to total roof removal, and one home had a few upper floor exterior walls ripped off. Numerous other homes in town sustained less severe damage, and two people were injured in Newburgh.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 20 tornadoes.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, producing several tornadoes across parts of the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nA high-end EF2 tornado caused significant damage just south of [[Eufaula, Alabama]], where multiple homes in a subdivision had their roofs torn off. A few of these homes sustained partial exterior wall loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Multiple other weak tornadoes were confirmed in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> A landspout tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT at the north edge of [[Richland, Washington]], causing no damage. A total of 15 tornadoes are confirmed.<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 164 tornadoes confirmed in the United States in April.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA few weak tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8, causing tree and structure damage. Later on the night of April 8, a large EF2 cone tornado touched down near [[Weiner, Arkansas]], completely destroying a mobile home. The tornado then struck [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one frail home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged or destroyed in residential areas of town.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Extensive tree damage occurred and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> Numerous tornadoes, all of which weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio that night as well. One EF1 tornado caused considerable damage to a brick building in downtown [[Mooresville, Indiana]]. Another EF1 tornado damaged two mobile homes, a garage, and trees near [[Wilkesville, Ohio]] on March 9 before the outbreak came to an end. Numerous reports of damaging straight line winds were also received throughout the event. A total of 31 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 29|F1 = 68|F2 = 21|F3 = 12|F4 = 2|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\nFrom the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major tornado outbreak unfolded across the [[Southeastern United States]], with more than 100 tornadoes touching down in 24 hours over two days. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 131 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Maryland. This event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city limits causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce three intense long-tracked tornadoes, including two rated EF4, that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center - PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. At 6:55 a.m. EDT, an embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another tornado emergency as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Nine EF3 tornadoes occurred on day two of the outbreak, including seven in [[South Carolina]] that resulted in a combined eight deaths, most notably the 3/4-mile wide EF3 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina|Hampton County]] that took the lives of five people near the towns of [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and Nixville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nWith 32 confirmed fatalities, it was the deadliest outbreak since the [[Tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "name_user": "ChessEric", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed incorrect date.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornadoes_of_2020"}
{"title_page": "Ernie Smith (tackle)", "text_new": "{{other people|Ernie Smith}}\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Ernie Smith\n|image=\n|caption=\n|position=[[Tackle (American football)|Tackle]]<br>[[Placekicker]]\n|number=45, 61\n|birth_date={{birth date|1909|11|26|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Spearfish, South Dakota]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1985|4|25|1909|11|26}}\n|death_place =[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|undraftedyear=\n|college=[[USC Trojans football|USC]]\n|teams=\n*[[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|1935}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1939}})\n|highlights=\n* First-Team [[All-Pro]] (1936)\n* Second-Team [[All-Pro]] (1937)\n* [[Pro Bowl]] (1939)\n* 2x [[NFL champion]] ([[1936 NFL Championship Game|1936]]) ([[1939 NFL Championship Game|1939]])\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1932 College Football All-America Team|1932]])\n* 2x College Football National Champion (1931, 1932)\n* All-Time USC Football Team\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=40\n|statlabel2=Games [[Starting lineup|started]]\n|statvalue2=25\n|statlabel3=\n|nfl=SMI264480\n|pfr=S/SmitEr23\n|CollegeHOF=1575\n}}\n\n'''Ernest Frederick Smith''' (November 26, 1909 \u2013 April 25, 1985) was an [[American football]] [[Tackle (American football)|tackle]] under coach [[Howard Jones (American football coach)|Howard Jones]] at the [[University of Southern California]] (USC).  He also handled the [[Placekicker|placekicking]] and [[Kickoff (American football)|kickoff]] duties for the men of Troy. Smith was a member of [[Phi Sigma Kappa]] fraternity. He played prominent roles in the Trojan [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] triumphs over [[Tulane University]] as a junior and against [[University of Pittsburgh]] as a senior. While in college, he was a member of the [[Spirit of Troy]] as a [[trombone]] player.\n\nHe played professionally from [[1935 Green Bay Packers season|1935]] to [[1939 Green Bay Packers season|1939]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]].\n\nHe was assistant football coach at Southern California two years, was a [[Major (United States)|Major]] in the [[United States Air Force]] between 1940 and 1945, and became an [[insurance underwriter]]. He worked with the [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]], was on the Rose Bowl Committee, an officer of the Southern California Symphony, and president of the Los Angeles chapter of the [[National Football Foundation]].\n\nHe was elected to the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1970.  In 2001, Athlon Sports named Smith to the All-Time USC Football Team as a defensive lineman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201192424/http://www.athlonsports.com/college-football/7989/usc-all-time-team |title=USC All-Time Team |accessdate=April 15, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nfl.com/players/erniesmith/profile?id=SMI264480 NFL.com player page]\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=|espn= |cbs= |yahoo= |fox= |si= |pfr=SmitEr23 |dbf= |rotoworld=}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Ernie Smith &ndash; championships, awards and honors\n| list1 =\n{{1931 USC Trojans football navbox}}\n{{1932 USC Trojans football navbox}}\n{{1936 Green Bay Packers}}\n{{1939 Green Bay Packers}}\n{{1932 College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Ernie}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:People from Spearfish, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from South Dakota]]\n[[Category:American football tackles]]\n[[Category:American football placekickers]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans football coaches]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n\n\n{{collegefootball-player-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Ernie Smith}}\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Ernie Smith\n|image=\n|caption=\n|position=[[Tackle (American football)|Tackle]]<br>[[Placekicker]]\n|number=45, 61\n|birth_date={{birth date|1909|11|26|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Spearfish, South Dakota]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1985|4|25|1909|11|26}}\n|death_place =[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|undraftedyear=\n|college=[[USC Trojans football|USC]]\n|teams=\n*[[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|1935}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1939}})\n|highlights=\n* First-Team [[All-Pro]] (1936)\n* Second-Team [[All-Pro]] (1937)\n* [[Pro Bowl]] (1939)\n* 2x [[NFL champion]] ([[1936 NFL Championship Game|1936]]) ([[1939 NFL Championship Game|1939]])\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1932 College Football All-America Team|1932]])\n* 2x College Football National Champion (1931, 1932)\n* All-Time USC Football Team\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=40\n|statlabel2=Games [[Starting lineup|started]]\n|statvalue2=25\n|statlabel3=\n|nfl=SMI264480\n|pfr=S/SmitEr23\n|CollegeHOF=1575\n}}\n\n'''Ernest Frederick Smith''' (November 26, 1909 \u2013 April 25, 1985) was an [[American football]] [[Tackle (American football)|tackle]] under coach [[Howard Jones (American football coach)|Howard Jones]] at the [[University of Southern California]] (USC).  He also handled the [[Placekicker|placekicking]] and [[Kickoff (American football)|kickoff]] duties for the men of Troy. Smith was a member of [[Phi Sigma Kappa]] fraternity. He played prominent roles in the Trojan [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] triumphs over [[Tulane University]] as a junior and against [[University of Pittsburgh]] as a senior. While in college, he was a member of the [[Spirit of Troy]] as a [[trombone]] player.\n\nHe played professionally from [[1935 Green Bay Packers season|1935]] to [[1939 Green Bay Packers season|1939]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]].\n\nHe was assistant football coach at Southern California two years, was a [[Major (United States)|Major]] in the [[United States Air Force]] between 1940 and 1945, and became an [[insurance underwriter]]. He worked with the [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]], was on the Rose Bowl Committee, an officer of the Southern California Symphony, and president of the Los Angeles chapter of the [[National Football Foundation]].\n\nHe was elected to the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1970.  In 2001, Athlon Sports named Smith to the All-Time USC Football Team as a defensive lineman  <ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201192424/http://www.athlonsports.com/college-football/7989/usc-all-time-team |title=USC All-Time Team |accessdate=April 15, 2020 }}</ref>.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nfl.com/players/erniesmith/profile?id=SMI264480 NFL.com player page]\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=|espn= |cbs= |yahoo= |fox= |si= |pfr=SmitEr23 |dbf= |rotoworld=}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Ernie Smith &ndash; championships, awards and honors\n| list1 =\n{{1931 USC Trojans football navbox}}\n{{1932 USC Trojans football navbox}}\n{{1936 Green Bay Packers}}\n{{1939 Green Bay Packers}}\n{{1932 College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Ernie}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:People from Spearfish, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from South Dakota]]\n[[Category:American football tackles]]\n[[Category:American football placekickers]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans football coaches]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n\n\n{{collegefootball-player-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernie_Smith_(tackle)"}
{"title_page": "Shell Game (TV series)", "text_new": "{{infobox television |\n | show_name = Shell Game\n | image = \n | caption = \n | genre = [[Comedy-drama]]\n | runtime = 60 minutes\n | company = Lou-Step Productions<br>[[Warner Bros. Television]] \n | creator = Carla Jean Wagner\n | producer = Alex Beaton<br>John Wirth\n | camera = \n | starring = [[James Read]]<br>[[Margot Kidder]]<br>[[Chip Zien]]<br>[[Marg Helgenberger]]\n | narrated = \n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | network = [[CBS]]\n | first_aired = {{start date|1987|1|8}}\n | last_aired = {{end date|1987|2|12}}\n | num_seasons = 1\n | num_episodes = 6\n | list_episodes = Shell Game (TV series)#Episodes\n}}\n\n'''''Shell Game''''' is an American [[comedy-drama]] [[television series]] that aired on [[CBS]] from January 8 until February 12, 1987.\n\n==Premise==\nTwo former con artists use their skills in a consumer-action show.<ref>{{cite web|author=TV Guide |url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/shell-game/cast/204352 |title=Shell Game Cast and Details|publisher=TV Guide |accessdate=2013-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[James Read]] as John Reid\n*[[Margot Kidder]] as Jennie Jerome\n*[[Chip Zien]] as Bert Luna\n*[[Marg Helgenberger]] as Natalie Thayer\n*Rod McCary as William Bauer\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Pilot\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|1|8}}\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |DirectedBy=Lou Antonio\n |WrittenBy=Carla Jean Wagner\n |ShortSummary= John hides Jennie after a con gone wrong. Jennie helps John into an asylum where an heiress is being held.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Norman's Parking Ticket\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|1|15}}\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |DirectedBy=Harry Harris\n |WrittenBy=Gerald Sanoff\n |ShortSummary= A man's car was ticketed and used for murder, but the man claims he was out of town.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=The Old Team\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|1|22}}\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |DirectedBy=Paul Krasny\n |WrittenBy= Nick Thiel & Kerry Ehrin\n |ShortSummary= The consumer-action show is on to a con done by Jennie and her father\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=The Upstairs Gardener\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|1|29}}\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |DirectedBy=Chris Leitch\n |WrittenBy=John Wirth\n |ShortSummary= An illegal alien is accused of killing an heiress.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Pai Gow\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|2|5}}\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |DirectedBy=Harry Mastrogeorge\n |WrittenBy=John Wells & Mitchell Fink\n |ShortSummary= When a man is charged with drunk driving and manslaughter, he claims he was set up.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Dead Wrong\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|2|12}}\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |DirectedBy=Chris Leitch\n |WrittenBy=John Wirth & John Wells\n |ShortSummary= Luna and Bauer are fired when they air an unsubstantiated arsonist story, Jennie and John makes a bet on who can solve the case first.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0092450|Shell Game}}\n* {{tv.com show|shell-game|Shell Game}}\n*[http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/shell-game/204352 TV Guide]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shell Game (Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:1987 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1987 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox television |\n | show_name = Shell Game\n | image = \n | caption = \n | genre = [[Comedy-drama]]\n | runtime = 60 minutes\n | company = Lou-Step Productions<br>[[Warner Bros. Television]] \n | creator = Carla Jean Wagner\n | producer = Alex Beaton<br>John Wirth\n | camera = \n | starring = [[James Read]]<br>[[Margot Kidder]]<br>[[Chip Zien]]\n | narrated = \n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | network = [[CBS]]\n | first_aired = {{start date|1987|1|8}}\n | last_aired = {{end date|1987|2|12}}\n | num_seasons = 1\n | num_episodes = 6\n | list_episodes = Shell Game (TV series)#Episodes\n}}\n\n'''''Shell Game''''' is an American [[comedy-drama]] [[television series]] that aired on [[CBS]] from January 8 until February 12, 1987.\n\n==Premise==\nTwo former con artists use their skills in a consumer-action show.<ref>{{cite web|author=TV Guide |url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/shell-game/cast/204352 |title=Shell Game Cast and Details|publisher=TV Guide |accessdate=2013-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[James Read]] as John Reid\n*[[Margot Kidder]] as Jennie Jerome\n*[[Chip Zien]] as Bert Luna\n*Rod McCary as William Bauer\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#39f;\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Pilot\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|1|8}}\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |DirectedBy=Lou Antonio\n |WrittenBy=Carla Jean Wagner\n |ShortSummary= John hides Jennie after a con gone wrong. Jennie helps John into an asylum where an heiress is being held.\n |LineColor=3399ff\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |Title=Norman's Parking Ticket\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1987|1|15}}\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |DirectedBy=Harry Harris\n |WrittenBy=Gerald Sanoff\n |ShortSummary= A man's car was ticketed and used for murder, but the man claims he was out of town.\n |LineColor=